Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["Example 3",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 "  If you did Exercise 3 of Section 1.3 you discovered how to simulate \
values of a random variable with a known p.m.f. on a finite state space.  Let \
us apply the ideas here to write a command to repeatedly simulate from the \
grade distribution in Example 2.\n\tThis can be done by encoding simulated \
uniform[0,1] observations in accordance with the grade distribution in \
formula (2). If, for example, such a uniform number takes a value in [0, \
4/21) we can call the result an ",
 StyleBox["A",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ".  Since the probability that a simulated uniform[0,1] observation falls \
into an interval is equal to the length of the interval, state ",
 StyleBox["A",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " will have probability 4/21 as desired. State ",
 StyleBox["B",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " must have probability 8/21, so we can call the result a ",
 StyleBox["B",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " if the uniform number falls into [4/21, 12/21), which has length 8/21.  \
Proceeding similarly for states ",
 StyleBox["C",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ", ",
 StyleBox["D",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ", and ",
 StyleBox["F",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ", we have the following command. (Encode ",
 StyleBox["A",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " as 4, ",
 StyleBox["B",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " as 3, etc. as in Activity 1.)"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{3.433353954580448*^9}],

