Cell[TextData[{
 "Since the probabilities of states 0-4 are .05, .09, .29, .38, and .19, this \
particular empirical histogram fits the theoretical distribution fairly well. \
 You might have noticed that although we are interested in simulating the \
selection of a random student, what we actually did in the command was to \
simulate a random variable ",
 StyleBox["Y",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " taking ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"[", 
    RowBox[{"0", ",", "1"}], "]"}], TraditionalForm]]],
 " to ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{"4", ",", "3", ",", "2", ",", "1", ",", "0"}], "}"}], 
   TraditionalForm]]],
 " as in Figure 3, with the same distribution as ",
 StyleBox["X",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ".  To produce the picture we have used ",
 StyleBox["Mathematica",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 "'s Which function to define the step function, and a utility contained in \
the KnoxProb7`Utilities` package called \n\n\t\t\tPlotStepFunction[function, \
domain, jumplist]\n\t\t\t\nwhich plots a right continuous step function on an \
interval with the given domain, with jumps at the given list of ",
 StyleBox["x",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " values.  It has a DotSize option as shown to control the size of the dots, \
and also accepts the AxesOrigin and PlotRange options, as does the Plot \
command. \[FilledSquare]"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{3.40397153159375*^9, 3.4408007867179313`*^9, 
  3.440801017376931*^9}],

