Cell["Two Special Distributions", "Subsection",
 FontWeight->"Bold"],

Cell["\<\
\tThe rest of this chapter is primarily a catalog of the most common discrete \
distributions, their moments, and their applications.  We will begin this \
catalog here by looking at two simple distributions that arise easily from \
work we have already done on random sampling: the discrete uniform \
distribution and the hypergeometric distribution. \
\>", "Text"],

Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["Example 7",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 "  When one item is sampled at random from a set of consecutive integers ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{"a", ",", 
     RowBox[{"a", "+", "1"}], ",", "...", ",", "b"}], "}"}], 
   TraditionalForm]]],
 ", since there are ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"(", 
    RowBox[{"b", "-", "a", "+", "1"}], ")"}], TraditionalForm]]],
 " equally likely states, the probability mass function of the selected item \
is clearly"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{
  3.424436569875*^9, {3.424440243078125*^9, 3.42444024609375*^9}, {
   3.4359673385895176`*^9, 3.4359673385955176`*^9}}],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{
    StyleBox["f",
     FontSlant->"Italic"], "(", 
    StyleBox["x",
     FontSlant->"Italic"], ")"}], " ", "=", " ", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
     FormBox[
      FractionBox["1", 
       RowBox[{"b", "-", "a", "+", "1"}]],
      TraditionalForm], " ", "if", " ", 
     StyleBox["x",
      FontSlant->"Italic"]}], " ", "\[Element]", " ", 
    FormBox[
     RowBox[{"{", 
      RowBox[{"a", ",", 
       RowBox[{"a", "+", "1"}], ",", "...", ",", "b"}], "}"}],
     TraditionalForm]}]}], TraditionalForm]], "DisplayFormulaNumbered",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.4359673454255176`*^9, 3.4359673458605175`*^9}}],

Cell[TextData[{
 "which is called the ",
 StyleBox["discrete uniform distribution",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " on ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{"a", ",", 
     RowBox[{"a", "+", "1"}], ",", "...", ",", "b"}], "}"}], 
   TraditionalForm]]],
 ". \n\tMany examples of this kind of random experiment spring to mind, from \
draft lotteries to dice rolling and other games of chance. Because states are \
equally likely, the probability that the sampled item ",
 StyleBox["X",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " falls into a set ",
 StyleBox["B",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " is simply the number of states in ",
 StyleBox["B",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " divided by the number of states in the whole space. \n\tUsually this \
distribution is used as a building block in other kinds of problems however.  \
There is a famous story, perhaps apocryphal, about German tanks in World War \
II, which apparently were numbered sequentially from 1 to the highest number. \
 Allied intelligence had observed a sample of tank numbers, and was \
interested in using the sample to estimate how many tanks the Germans had. \n\
\tTo formulate a mathematical model, suppose that tank numbers ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["X", "1"], TraditionalForm]]],
 ", ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["X", "2"], TraditionalForm]]],
 ", ... , ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["X", "n"], TraditionalForm]]],
 " are observed in the sample, suppose also that events involving different ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["X", "i"], TraditionalForm]]],
 "'s are mutually independent (we will have a good definition of independent \
random variables later), and suppose that each ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["X", "i"], TraditionalForm]]],
 " has the discrete uniform distribution on ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{"1", ",", "2", ",", "...", ",", "\[Theta]"}], "}"}], 
   TraditionalForm]]],
 ", where \[Theta] is the total number of tanks in existence.  Note that the \
c.d.f. ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"F", "(", "x", ")"}], " ", "=", " ", 
    RowBox[{
     StyleBox["P",
      FontSlant->"Plain"], "[", 
     RowBox[{"X", "\[LessEqual]", "x"}], "]"}]}], TraditionalForm]]],
 " of this distribution would have the value ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"(", 
    RowBox[{"x", "/", "\[Theta]"}], ")"}], TraditionalForm]]],
 " at each state ",
 StyleBox["x",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " (why?).  We can then proceed just as in Example 4 to obtain the c.d.f. and \
mass function of ",
 StyleBox["Y",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " = max",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{
     FormBox[
      SubscriptBox["X", "1"],
      TraditionalForm], ",", 
     FormBox[
      SubscriptBox["X", "2"],
      TraditionalForm], ",", "...", ",", 
     FormBox[
      SubscriptBox["X", "n"],
      TraditionalForm]}], "}"}], TraditionalForm]]],
 ", the largest tank number observed in the sample.  (You should fill in the \
details.) "
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.4359673641205177`*^9, 3.4359673641235175`*^9}}],

Cell[BoxData[
 FormBox[
  RowBox[{" ", 
