Cell[TextData[{
 "\tOne sensible way of proceeding from here is to have ",
 StyleBox["Mathematica",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " compute the expected value of this distribution for a fixed sample size ",
 StyleBox["n",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " and various values of \[Theta], and choose as our estimate of \[Theta] the \
one for which the expected value of ",
 StyleBox["Y",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " comes closest to the highest tank number actually observed in the sample.  \
Suppose for the sake of the example that 40 tanks are observed and the \
highest tank number in the sample is 125. The first function below is the \
p.m.f. of the maximum tank number in the sample, as a function of the sample \
size ",
 StyleBox["n",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " and the highest tank number in the population of tanks \[Theta].  The \
second function gives the expected value of the highest tank number in the \
sample, as a function of ",
 StyleBox["n",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " and \[Theta]."
}], "Text"],

